`DataProvider` requieres an `Object[][]` because that will be the two dimension array with the parameters of all executions of the `@Test` that uses that `DataProvider`.

For instance, if the `Object[][]` returned is this:

```
      data[0][0] = &quot;Peter&quot;; 
      data[0][1] = &quot;18&quot;; 

     data[1][0] = &quot;Ross&quot;; 
     data[1][1] = &quot;45&quot;; 

     data[2][0] = &quot;Diana&quot;; 
     data[2][1] = &quot;11&quot;;
```

The `@Test` method, which must then be defined with 2 parameters, will be executed 3 times. The first one with the patameters `Peter` and `18`, the second one with `Ross` and `45`, and so on.

That is how a `DataProvider` works. So you will have to manually parse the `properties` file and with ots contents build the `Object[][]` that will serve the `@Test` method.

So your `DataProvider` method, simplofied for a single sample as in your question, should look like this:
```
@DataProvider(name = &quot;browserProvider&quot;)
    public Object[][] getData() throws IOException {
        
        FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream(
                &quot;C:\\Users\\user\\git\\Quntrix-Training\\automation\\src\\test\\resources\\config.properties&quot;);
        Properties p = new Properties();
        p.load(fis);

        Object[][] data = new Object[1][1];
        data[0][0] = p.getProperty(&quot;BrowserType&quot;);
        return data;
    }
```

And if in the `properties` there is more data, just iterate or retrieve as you need and keep filling the `Object[][]`.

Despite the answer you have marked as correct solves your particular issue I would like to give some insight because I assume that you misunderstand the concept of data providers.

**Why does it return `Object[][]`?**

Data providers is a mechanism that allows to multiply a single test so that having that single test and `N` pieces of input data you would have `N` tests.

This is where `Object[][]` comes from. Basically `Object[][]` is an array of `Object[]` where &quot;outer array&quot; holds the sequences of parameters for different test and each sequence is represented by &quot;inner array&quot;.

For example you have a method:

```java
public void testMyStuff(String a, String b){
   ...
}
```

**This method takes two arguments**, so that the &quot;horizontal&quot; size of your `Object[][]` would be **2**.

Now if you want to split this single test into three different tests you need to have &quot;vertical&quot; size of your `Object[][]` equal to **3**.

```java
Object[][] test = {
        {&quot;A1&quot;, &quot;B1&quot;},
        {&quot;A2&quot;, &quot;B2&quot;},
        {&quot;A3&quot;, &quot;B3&quot;}
};
```

So that you would have the following execution sequence:

```java
testMyStuff(&quot;A1&quot;, &quot;B1&quot;);
testMyStuff(&quot;A2&quot;, &quot;B2&quot;);
testMyStuff(&quot;A3&quot;, &quot;B3&quot;);
```

**So why is it not your case?**

You have a single property file where you have a single value for your property. This is not the pattern for data providers. It is better to poll property value straight from your test.

